metadata.name: Disjoint and Disoriented #16
metadata.description:
Disjoint and Disoriented is about the abstract structure formed by the equalities and oppositions of its parts.

It might require high processing power depending on its features. A good desktop or laptop is recommended.

There are three render options available as url parameters in live mode:
- size=XXXX (up to 5760 pixels)
- texture=0 (disable canvas texture for print)
- shader=1 (use the shader throughout the painting process, can be heavy)

Created with p5.js and GLSL
dmarchi and lunarean, 2022.

metadata.name: Sketch B #45
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch B remains simple. The basic grid of Sketch A is there, but is starting to be filled. Grid lines are trimmed as if sketched. Colors continue to be borrowed from Echos/Orbits and new colors from Bent are incorporated. Grid size, padding, line thickness, fill color, and fill percentage and patterns vary.

metadata.name: Astraea's Loom #51
metadata.description:
A true collaboration of styles between Rose Jackson (@in_cloudlands) and Liam Egan (@neuromantic6).

Inspired by the weaving of cloth, this generative piece takes textures created lovingly by Rose and feeds it through a digital loom, weaving new cloth from the weft.

Preview images will differ slightly from the final output due to differing rendering methods in the preview system, and different resolutions may produce slightly different images.

For licensing information please see license.md

metadata.name: a fleeting moment #197
metadata.description:
Abstract expressionism always has been, and always will be, my first love. With this piece, the initial premise was "can I write a bit of code that will render images in the style that I actually paint in real life?" 

It took several full days of poking and prodding, and I departed from the original mission once I had what I was looking for, but in general, I think I succeeded. My wife was looking over my shoulder at one point, and thought I was looking at a scan of one of my actual paintings, which sounds like success to me. 

Created with love in p5.js

metadata.name: Many worlds #193
metadata.description:
An interactive chaotic attractor based on a circular harmonograph.

This piece rewards patience.  After the initial structure forms, watch the attractor develop as more iterations are added and the details resolve.  The image will continue to refine itself forever; there is no limit on the iteration number.  Pause, unpause, generate and export jpgs at very high resolutons (see controls below).

This is a generalisation of a piece donated to the Edible East science and art trail on our global sustainable food future, and 100% of every sale and secondary royal1ties will be donated to local food banks.

Controls:  

To stop/restart the attractor iterating, press SPACE.
To switch to a high resolution canvas, press 1-9.  The canvas width will become n*1000 by n*1000 (so 2000x2000 if you press '2') and the attractor will restart.
To export the current canvas as a jpeg, press X.
To update the whole image with current data, press U (helpful if using a high resolution).
To invert, press I.

metadata.name: Organicon, variation I #405
metadata.description:
Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
A unique generator creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation I is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. Warning: the preview thumbnail is a pale shadow of live view.

Interface: a first mouse click clears the screen, creates an new iteration and enables active mode. In active mode each iteration remains on screen for a limited amount of time before being replaced by the next. A second mouse click disables active mode. In active mode a small dot is displayed in the lower right corner. '+' and '-' zoom in and out.

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #206
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Gestalt #865
metadata.description:
"Gestalt" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

A flurry of many elements derived from my past (and future) strewn across a single canvas. As random as things seem, collectively time tends to reveal hints of order in the chaos. Sometimes, more is more.

Controls:
• Left-click/tap reassembles the piece with one less element each time
• 'R' reassembles the piece with all elements
• 'S' saves the output

“𝚃𝚑𝚎 𝚠𝚑𝚘𝚕𝚎 𝚒𝚜 𝚐𝚛𝚎𝚊𝚝𝚎𝚛 𝚝𝚑𝚊𝚗 𝚝𝚑𝚎 𝚜𝚞𝚖 𝚘𝚏 𝚒𝚝𝚜 𝚙𝚊𝚛𝚝𝚜.”

Made in p5js

Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: MODERN TITANS #1
metadata.description:
Modern Titans live in a disorienting, symbolic world in which life and death are omnipresent and is intertwined with primal connections between biology and technology. 

This project deploys expressions of emotional adaptation and cognitive resiliency as keys to surviving in the world of Modern Titans.


Genesis generative image project by @dehiscenceart with custom code by @LimnDigital.

4 Traits 
18 heads
18 rainbows
18 graffiti layers
17 gradient layers

= 99,144 possible combinations


Save your minted Artwork (or any edition) in Live Mode by pressing:
‘s’ or ‘S’ to save at current canvas size.
‘f’ or ‘F’ to save at Full size, 1250 x 1250px.
‘t’ or ‘T’ to save at Twitter Tweet size, 1200 x 1200px.

metadata.name: Fantasized Telekinetic Obliteration #69
metadata.description:
An exploration on the ways in which mental energy might be captured and converted to kinetic destruction.

Each piece begins with an abstract shape. The shape is subjected to a field of disruptors, which contains a combination of beams and bombs. Beams slice through material, shearing fragments generally in the direction the beam is traveling. Bombs shatter material apart and eject shards away from the blast site.

All matter is conserved. That is, if the exploded and scattered fragments were reverted back to their initial positions, there would be a fully intact shape. No virtual particles. 🖤

Some structures may be annihilated. Others may take minor damage — or perhaps, none at all. Consult the “telekinetic power” feature for a full assessment.

---
- made with p5js
- press “s” to save png

metadata.name: Frost's Road #19
metadata.description:
Do you take the less traveled road and dispel the wonder of what might have been?  Or, do you preserve the mystery by gazing down the overgrown, winding path savoring the speculation--never to be disappointed or have your wonder sated?

Frost's Road celebrates the obvious and enigmatic themes of Frost's poem, "The Road Not Taken."  A generative path to nowhere? Or someplace special?  Frost's Road subtly captures the obviousness of a vacant path, and the questions that lingers about why is that.

Created with p5js.

Press the Down Arrow to save the frame as a png.
Click or tap the canvas to toggle full screen mode.
Output Size: 995 x 1080.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #421
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.
